{{italic title}} '''''Kompetenz-kompetenz''''', or '''competence-competence''', is a [[jurisprudence|jurisprudential]] [[legal doctrine|doctrine]] whereby a legal body, such as a [[court]] or [[arbitral tribunal]], may have competence, or [[jurisdiction]], to rule as to the extent of its own competence on an issue before it. The concept arose in the [[Federal Constitutional Court of Germany]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lo|first=P. Y.|title=Master of One's Own Court|journal=Hong Kong Law Journal|year=2004|volume=34|page=54|id=34 Hong Kong L.J. 47, 54|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/Page?handle=hein.journals/honkon34&id=56|via=[[HeinOnline]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> Since then, ''kompetenz-kompetenz'' has often been important in [[international arbitration]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dulic|first=Adrianna|title=''First Options of Chicago, Inc. v. Kaplan'' and the Kompetenz-Kompetenz Principle|journal=Pepperdine Dispute Resolution Law Journal|year=2002|volume=2|issue=1|pages=77–97|id=2 Pepp. Disp. Resol. L.J. 77|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/Page?handle=hein.journals/pepds2&id=85|via=[[HeinOnline]]|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Oehmke|first=Thomas H.|title=Commercial Arbitration|edition=3d|author2=with Joan M. Brovins|chapter=International Arbitration|volume=2|at=§ 41:65}}</ref>
