[[File:The Taking of Christ-Caravaggio (c.1602).jpg|250px|thumb|''[[The Taking of Christ]]'',  1602. [[National Gallery of Ireland]], [[Dublin]]]]
'''''The Lost Painting: The Quest for a Caravaggio Masterpiece''''' is a non-fiction book by the author of ''[[A Civil Action]]'', [[Jonathan Harr]].  The book traces the recent discovery of a [[Caravaggio]] painting, by comparing two copies of the painting and trying to figure out which one is the original ''[[The Taking of Christ]]'' (c. 1602).<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|title='The Lost Painting': The Caravaggio Trail|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/13/books/review/13handy.html?ex=1289538000&en=dcf98c9a2e8d776a&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss|accessdate=25 June 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 November 2005}}</ref>  The book is an extension of an article that first appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]''. One of the people whose life is recounted in the book is the Oxford philosopher and ontologist of the [[infosphere]] [[Luciano Floridi]].

''Variety'' reports that Miramax might produce a film version of the book.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fleming |first1=Michael |title=Miramax finds ‘Lost’ |url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/miramax-finds-lost-1117952296/ |website=Variety |date=October 20, 2006}}</ref>

